
Executive summary

Overall, the school has built a meaningful base of activity and revenue, with 5,792 total registrations, 2,520 unique attendees, and 478 unique classes, generating $381,431 in collected revenue. That works out to about 12.1 registrations per class, $789 in average revenue per class, and an average class price of $78. The current program is therefore operating at real scale, with a broad catalog and a sizable returning customer base.

The strongest high-level signal is that the business is increasingly supported by loyalty rather than one-time demand. From the retention view, 79.8% of registrations come from repeat attendees, which means most program volume is being driven by people who have already engaged once and come back again. That is an important sign of health: the school is not relying solely on constant new-customer replacement, but is building an audience that returns over time.

Operationally, classes are filling moderately well, but there is still room to improve utilization. The overall average fill rate is 59.8%, and using the price-band sellout rates as a program-wide proxy, roughly 32% of classes fill to capacity. The school is therefore generating strong participation, but still has significant open-seat capacity across much of the catalog. In practical terms, this suggests the next stage of growth likely comes less from adding raw volume everywhere and more from improving mix, pricing, and conversion into the classes that already resonate.

The category mix is highly concentrated. Art is the clear anchor of the school, accounting for 2,513 registrations (43.4%) and $202,216 in revenue (53.0%) — more than half of total revenue on its own. After Art, the next-largest contributors are Storytelling (717 registrations; $40,470), Outdoor Education (648; $26,188), Wellness (563; $25,585), Culinary (551; $32,930), and Fiber Arts (431; $38,764). This means the school is not equally balanced across offerings: it is led decisively by one flagship category, with a second tier of supporting programs.

The time-series views suggest the program has expanded its monthly class cadence and revenue base over time, though with some month-to-month volatility. Monthly class counts rise materially from the earlier period into 2025–2026, with many recent months running in the 20+ class range, versus a much smaller base in late 2023. Revenue also steps up meaningfully in the later period, with multiple months above $20K and peaks above $25K in early 2026. That pattern suggests the school has been scaling both supply and revenue, even if demand still lands unevenly across specific months.

Taken together, the state of the school is healthy and maturing: there is a sizable customer base, repeat attendance is doing much of the commercial work, Art remains the core economic engine, and recent periods show evidence of a larger and more productive program than the earlier baseline. The biggest strategic opportunity appears to be optimizing the existing engine — strengthening class fill, sharpening mix, and leaning into the categories and price points that already produce the strongest returns.

